## Steps to Reproduce

Create a documentation comment like the following:

```dart
/// See also:
///
///  * There is a great class you should really know about, [String]. If you don't
///    know about the [String] class, you've not been paying attention.
```

If you paste this into IntelliJ, it will linkify the first instance of `[String]`, but not the second one. It seems that any reference on the subsequent lines of a bulleted list are not recognized as being symbols, probably because the parser is assuming that any line beginning with three spaces is a <pre> section in Markdown.  I think it's supposed to be four or more, really, but only if it's not part of a bulleted or numbered list. Maybe that's not the cause, but in any case, it doesn't work.

And it's not just linking: rename operations on any symbol that isn't recognized in this way will also fail: it'll skip renaming those symbols referenced in subsequent lines of the list.

comment_data.body:
This is done by the Dart plugin. I'll create an issue in their repo later. I noticed that if the second line was indented at the same level as the star (three spaces) then the link was enabled.

@jwren

This is an issue in the analyzer, not the plugin. The proper repo is dart-lang/sdk. I used to be able to move issues but lost that ability as security was tightened.

@alexander-doroshko sorry for the noise in YouTrack.
I'm happy to re-file in dart-lang/sdk.

Yes, apparently it is intentionally disabled in the parser.
https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/blob/28e8202c1408c3dc066cc5c93b10026b17b75095/pkg/_fe_analyzer_shared/lib/src/parser/parser_impl.dart#L8478
Yes, that's correct, but only if the line isn't part of a Markdown bulleted list paragraph.

For instance, in the Markdown view in IntelliJ:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8867023/168917985-6a97b78a-fc97-49ee-a745-746a8f519eae.png)

All the lines except for the "This is a new paragraph" are indented by the same amount.

title: Documentation comment symbol links not recognized when in subsequent lines of bulleted lists.
